    }
  ],
  "fileEdits": [
    {
      "path": "page/sections/beat-04.md",
      "find": "> If a candidate's numbers just get bigger, same direction, longer arrow, does its score change?",
      "replace": "> If you double c1's length exactly, same direction, just twice as long, does the number double too?"
    },
    {
      "path": "page/sections/beat-04.md",
      "find": "It climbs. Every single time. Stretch a candidate's arrow without changing its direction at all, an exaggerated \"5 years\" where the truth was \"3,\" an inflated confidence score, and the meter goes up anyway. The direction, the thing that was supposed to represent fit, never moved. The score climbed on size alone.",
      "replace": "It does, exactly. Double c1's length without changing its direction at all, an exaggerated \"6 years\" where the truth was \"3,\" an inflated confidence score, and the number doubles right along with it. The meter is linear in each input: double one arrow and you double the output, clean and predictable. The direction, the thing that was supposed to represent fit, never moved. The score climbed on size alone."
    }
  ],
  "summary": "Replaced beat-04's already-answered 'does its score change?' prediction with the quantitative 'does the number double?' and rewrote the reveal to teach the meter is linear in each input, feeding the cheapest-fix breadcrumb, across storyboard, video, and page."
}

